The receiver is machined from aircraft grade billet aluminum alloy and is the interface for the barrel, bolt assembly, trigger assembly and magazine. A recoil lug of hardened steel is integrated into the receiver. The entire unit is fixed to the stock, eliminating temperature induced distortion. The outer surface is hard anodized. title: For Sale:  Rare Colt SAA Manufactured in 1874 Has both Colt and Kopec Letters
postcontent: For sale here is a very interesting, and very old Colt SAA manufactured in 1874. It is one of those anomaly revolvers that occasionally show up that has an authentic martial “U.S.” stamped frame, but spent its entire life in the civilian market. It has all matching numbers and is in good physical shape with a few timing mechanical issues that I am sure can be fixed. No Reserve and Free shipping! Please read on. The mystery as to how “U.S.” marked Cavalry revolver frames ended up on “always” civilian revolvers may have been solved, but to my knowledge, there are still only educated opinions as to its actual genesis. This issue is covered by Graham, Kopec, and Moore in chapter 1 of their classic book, A Study of the Colt Single Action Revolver (1976) where two possibilities are proffered. One possibility is that the ordinance inspector at the time (Ainsworth) set aside frames which were already stamped “U.S.” by Colt that did not pass military specification, but were otherwise serviceable, for later use by Colt on civilian models, and the other possibility is that an urgent request for civilian revolvers was honored by Colt which took priority over the military contract and required the use of “U.S.” stamped frames immediately available for assembly. There is evidence that both of these actions actually did take place. Please keep in mind that we are only referring to revolvers that never saw life in the military before entering the civilian market and not revolvers, such as “buy backs”, that were resold as civilian revolvers after a good life in the military (they also will have a “U.S.” stamped frame), and we are certainly not talking about revolvers with forged stamps. This one is genuine! One other possibility is that this revolver is a very early “overrun”, although it does not have the usual ordinance sub-inspector markings that most overruns will have. In his book, Cavalry and Artillery Revolvers, A Continuing Story (1994), Kopec states that early overruns (i.e. pre-1875) will not have any sub-inspector markings. So, this just might be a very rare, early military overrun. Who really knows? In any case, this revolver has quite a story to tell and will make a great addition to any Colt SAA collection! This revolver comes with both a Colt and Kopec letter. I will state though, although I have nothing but respect for the honored Kopec, his letter offers little but added confusion as to the revolver’s actual history. In the letter, Mr. Kopec seemingly contradicts his own research (as stated above) when he states that this revolver “cannot” be an overrun because it does not have the Ainsworth “A” anywhere on it, but yet he is the one that stated in his book that pre-1875 overruns (which this would be) will not have the markings. He also provides a reason for the “U.S.” marking that is little more than circular mumbo-jumbo (sorry, I really do not mean to be disrespectful). The Kopek letter does provide a good rundown of the revolvers shortcomings which I list below: • The ejector tube is a second-style replacement and the ejector head is the later “oval” style. • The base-pin screw is an oversized replacement. • The barrel has been shortened from 7 ½ inches to 4 ¾ inches with the front sight repositioned a half-inch from the muzzle. • The grips are modern manufactured replacement (no timeframe given…they look pretty old). • The mainspring has been lightened with a deeply cut groove. • A tiny slot has been cut into the base of the trigger guard strap in an effort to possibly remove a frozen mainspring screw. And…the timing is off, only three clicks and the cylinder can moved independently. It’s old, not perfect!! One last thing, Kopec makes an entirely unsupported comment in his letter that this revolver may have “served its useful life in Mexico”. This revolver was shipped to New York City on October 7, 1874 (Incidentally, there is a picture of a revolver from this very same shipment in Graham, Kopec, and Moore (1974), p.13). So how did it end up in Mexico? No connection or explanation given by Kopec. Hmmmm, probably not Amigo.
